abstract: The mayor raised $394,000 from a combination of small-dollar New York City donors and much larger contributions from outside the five boroughs.
snippet: The mayor raised $394,000 from a combination of small-dollar New York City donors and much larger contributions from outside the five boroughs.
lead_paragraph: Mayor Bill de Blasio raised significantly more money for his re-election campaign from donors outside of New York City than in it over the last two months, according to a new filing, thanks largely to a last-minute national fund-raising swing.

abstract: Officials took a cautious approach to Tuesday’s storm after learning painful lessons from recent winters. And, unlike in past storms, there were few complaints.
snippet: Officials took a cautious approach to Tuesday’s storm after learning painful lessons from recent winters. And, unlike in past storms, there were few complaints.
lead_paragraph: In New York City, the arrival of a major snowstorm offers a high-stakes challenge for state and city officials. This time, for once, there were few complaints.

byline_original: By Emma G. Fitzsimmons and Kate Taylor

abstract: A financial district offering from the team behind Blue Ribbon; Jonathan Benno to leave Lincoln Ristorante; Le Périgord closes; and other restaurant news.
snippet: A financial district offering from the team behind Blue Ribbon; Jonathan Benno to leave Lincoln Ristorante; Le Périgord closes; and other restaurant news.
lead_paragraph: MAJORELLE The new restaurant in the Lowell Hotel is finally about to open. Taking a look at the elegant dining room designed by Michael S. Smith, and its château-worthy architectural details like engaged columns and egg-and-dart moldings, it’s easy to understand why it took so long. Past a leather-trimmed bar called Jacques (as in the artist Jacques Majorelle, whose gardens are a treasure of Marrakesh, Morocco), the restaurant has 75 or so seats, about 20 of them in a compact, skylit garden, and a comfortable library/lounge with a fireplace is adjacent to the dining room. Charles Masson, one of the city’s rare guardians of classic French cuisine and service, will run the restaurant. And, with Christian Delouvrier consulting and Mr. Masson’s input, the chef, Mario Fortuna, is creating a menu he described as marrying traditional French with the Mediterranean, even crossing the sea for an occasional taste of Morocco, with a tagine. Highlights include a rich onion tart, warm sausage with potatoes, risotto of wild mushrooms, bass with Champagne and caviar, and steak au poivre. There will be tableside service for carving a chicken for two and finishing a baba au rhum. The pastry chef, David Carmichael, will produce breads from grains milled in-house. “You can’t beat fresh flour for nutrition,” he said. A bar menu has lighter fare like chicken liver mousse and ceviche, but it’s not above offering a hamburger. (Opens Wednesday): 28 East 63rd Street, 212-935-2888, majorelleny.com.

abstract: The list of issues that could open a new rift between Mr. Trump and the Chinese leader is long, including the deployment of American antimissile batteries in South Korea and trade tensions.
snippet: The list of issues that could open a new rift between Mr. Trump and the Chinese leader is long, including the deployment of American antimissile batteries in South Korea and trade tensions.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When President Trump and President Xi Jinping of China sit down for their first meeting next month in Palm Beach, Fla., they could use the balmy breezes and tranquil views at the Mar-a-Lago resort: Relations between the United States and China are as complex and chilly as they have been since the early days of the Reagan administration.

headline_main: A Breezy Resort, and a Thorny Agenda, for Trump’s Meeting With Xi Jinping of China
headline_print_headline: A Breezy Resort, and a Thorny Agenda, for a U.S.-China Meeting

abstract: A potential agreement to sell a stake in a New York skyscraper would be extremely lucrative for the family of Jared Kushner, and could protect the Chinese buyers from scrutiny.
snippet: A potential agreement to sell a stake in a New York skyscraper would be extremely lucrative for the family of Jared Kushner, and could protect the Chinese buyers from scrutiny.
lead_paragraph: A New York real estate company owned by the family of President Trump’s son-in-law has been negotiating to sell a $400 million stake in its Fifth Avenue flagship skyscraper to a Chinese insurance company with ties to leading families of the Communist Party.

abstract: The city says Verizon failed to honor an agreement to build a citywide Fios network, shutting out “tens of thousands” of prospective customers.
snippet: The city says Verizon failed to honor an agreement to build a citywide Fios network, shutting out “tens of thousands” of prospective customers.
lead_paragraph: Nine years after Verizon promised to make its high-speed Fios internet service available to every household in New York City, the city sued the company on Monday, saying it had failed to keep that pledge.

abstract: We asked readers to suggest actors for the HBO mini-series about the 2016 presidential campaign from the journalists behind “Game Change.”
snippet: We asked readers to suggest actors for the HBO mini-series about the 2016 presidential campaign from the journalists behind “Game Change.”
lead_paragraph: When news broke that the reporters Mark Halperin and John Heilemann would be writing a book chronicling Donald J. Trump’s presidential campaign — and that this book would be turned into an HBO mini-series — we wanted to help Tom Hanks, the executive producer, and the rest of the principals, by offering some casting suggestions.

abstract: The move by the insurer follows a big fourth-quarter loss and pressure by investors including Carl Icahn.
snippet: The move by the insurer follows a big fourth-quarter loss and pressure by investors including Carl Icahn.
lead_paragraph: Nearly nine years after the insurance giant American International Group peered into the abyss of the global financial crisis, the latest in a long line of new chief executives will try to return it to its pre-crisis heights.

headline_print_headline: A.I.G. Chief Out After Big Loss

abstract: Analysts say the network is spreading disinformation and undermining Western democracies, but its executives say it is just providing an “alternative” view.
snippet: Analysts say the network is spreading disinformation and undermining Western democracies, but its executives say it is just providing an “alternative” view.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — The London newsroom and studios of RT, the television channel and website formerly known as Russia Today, are ultramodern and spacious, with spectacular views from the 16th floor overlooking the Thames and the London Eye. And, its London bureau chief, Nikolay A. Bogachikhin, jokes, “We overlook MI5 and we’re near MI6,” Britain’s domestic and foreign intelligence agencies.
